label: City Planning Rental Replacement Completions (#) - Total

options.title: City Planning Rental Replacement Completions (#) - Total

custom.dataSource: Canada Mortgage and Housing Corporation, Special Request by City Planning, 2006 - 2018; City Planning analysis
custom.cityPerspective: CMHC's Starts and Completions Survey is based on building permit data and conducted through site visits to confirm that new housing units have reached set stages in the construction process. Because the number of units and/or intended market of a residential building can change from the time a building permit is issued to the time a building is ready for occupancy, each year the Housing Policy team conducts a manual review of rental completions on a site-by-site basis using custom (address-level) data from CMHC and City records in order to get the most accurate picture of rental housing development in the City as possible. Housing Policy works with City Planning's Research & Information unit and the Housing Secretariat to identify which completions are assisted rental, condominium registered, and/or rental replacement units. The figures presented here reflect City Planning's best estimates of rental construction based on this annual review.

custom.cityPerspective: Data Note: 1. Secondary rental are rental housing units which are not 'purpose-built', such as rented condominiums, rented houses, and secondary units within houses. In contrast to purpose-built rental, most housing that enters the secondary rental market is initially built as ownership housing and rented out at some later date to accommodate rental demand that is not met through the primary rental market. Exceptions to this are social and affordable rental housing, which are technically secondary rental.

label: City Planning Gross Rental Completions (#) - Total

options.title: City Planning Gross Rental Completions (#) - Total

custom.dataSource: Canada Mortgage and Housing Corporation, Special Request by City Planning, 2006 - 2018; City Planning analysis
custom.cityPerspective: CMHC's Starts and Completions Survey is based on building permit data and conducted through site visits to confirm that new housing units have reached set stages in the construction process. Because the number of units and/or intended market of a residential building can change from the time a building permit is issued to the time a building is ready for occupancy, each year the Housing Policy team conducts a manual review of rental completions on a site-by-site basis using custom (address-level) data from CMHC and City records in order to get the most accurate picture of rental housing development in the City as possible. Housing Policy works with City Planning's Research & Information unit and the Housing Secretariat to identify which completions are assisted rental, condominium registered, and/or rental replacement units. The figures presented here reflect City Planning's best estimates of rental construction based on this annual review.

custom.cityPerspective: CMHC's Starts and Completions Survey is based on building permit data and conducted through site visits to confirm that new housing units have reached set stages in the construction process. Because the number of units and/or intended market of a residential building can change from the time a building permit is issued to the time a building is ready for occupancy, each year the Housing Policy team conducts a manual review of rental completions on a site-by-site basis using custom (address-level) data from CMHC and City records in order to get the most accurate picture of rental housing development in the City as possible. Housing Policy works with City Planning's Research & Information unit and the Housing Secretariat to identify which completions are assisted rental, condominium registered, and/or rental replacement units. options.title: Primary Rental Apartment Vacancy Rate (%) by Rent Band - >150% of AMR - 1-bedroom

custom.dataSource: Canada Mortgage and Housing Corporation, Special Request by City Planning, 2018
custom.cityPerspective:
1. AMR = Average Market Rent as reported by CMHC in its annual Rental Market Report. 
2. 100% AMR = the City's affordable rent threshold. 150% AMR = the City's mid-range rent threshold.
3. Data is for primary rental apartments (purpose-built rental) with 3 or more units only.
4. Data is provided to the City by CMHC through special request.
5. City Planning has these statistics for 2004-2018 (all years).
